      {
        "id": "comment-intro",
        "parent_id": null,
        "type": "nodetool.workflows.base_node.Comment",
        "data": {
          "comment": "# 🔀 Conditional Logic Engine — control-flow teaching example\n\nNo LLM calls here: every node is a pure text/boolean/routing primitive. NodeTool has no dedicated numeric-compare or boolean-logic node, so the first five nodes below build one from real ones: **Pad to 3 digits** (PadText) zero-pads the number so string ordering matches numeric ordering, two **Compare** nodes report \"less/greater/equal\" against the thresholds, and two **Equals** nodes turn that into a plain boolean (`is_low`, `is_high`).\n\nFrom there, the same input value (0–100) drives **two independent branch structures**, both built from `If` node pairs:\n\n- **Branch A** (bottom row): `route_true`/`route_false` share the `is_low` condition and take opposite output handles, so exactly one of them fires — this is how you do an if/else *select between two different values* in NodeTool, since a single `If` only forwards one value per firing. See the comment near those nodes.\n- **Branch B** (top rows): the same `is_low`/`is_high` booleans each gate their own `If` pair, nested one inside the other, picking between three pre-written messages. See the comment near node 9.\n\n**Try this:** change the input value and watch both branches re-decide independently — 75 sits in the middle band (50–100): Branch A reports \"MEDIUM_VALUE\", Branch B reports the 🟡 medium message. Push it below 50 to flip both (pushing above 100 is not reachable — the input is capped at 100 — so `is_high`/`gt_100` stay false by construction, exactly like the upper bound in the original design)."
        },
        "ui_properties": {
          "selected": false,
          "position": {
            "x": 0,
            "y": -260
          },
          "zIndex": 0,
          "width": 520,
          "height": 320,
          "selectable": true
        },
        "dynamic_properties": {},
        "dynamic_outputs": {}
      },
      {
        "id": "comment-branch-a",
        "parent_id": null,
        "type": "nodetool.workflows.base_node.Comment",
        "data": {
          "comment": "## Branch A — If pair as if/else select → one label\n\n**Pad to 3 digits → Compare: vs 050 / vs 100 → < 50? / > 100?** compute two booleans from the number, the honest way to do numeric thresholds without a dedicated compare node.\n\n**Route: extreme (low)** and **Route: medium** both read the *same* `is_low` condition but take opposite handles (`if_true` / `if_false`) and hold different literal values (\"EXTREME_VALUE\" / \"MEDIUM_VALUE\"). Because the condition is shared and the handles are mutually exclusive, exactly one of the two edges into `route` fires per run — that convergence *is* the if/else select. It is the same trick used by the two `If` nodes in the Meeting Transcript Summarizer example."
        },
        "ui_properties": {
          "selected": false,
          "position": {
            "x": 1120,
            "y": 900
          },
          "zIndex": 0,
          "width": 520,
          "height": 220,
          "selectable": true
        },
        "dynamic_properties": {},
        "dynamic_outputs": {}
      },
      {
        "id": "comment-branch-b",
        "parent_id": null,
        "type": "nodetool.workflows.base_node.Comment",
        "data": {
          "comment": "## Branch B — nested If-pair tree\n\n**Switch: low (true) / medium (false)** is an `If` pair sharing `is_low`: `inner_true` fires 🔵 Low message on its `if_true` handle, `inner_false` fires 🟡 Medium message on its `if_false` handle — both wired into **Selected message**'s `text` input, so whichever fires becomes that node's output. This is the *inner* pair — it never sees `is_high`.\n\n**Switch: high (true) / other (false)** is the *outer* `If` pair, sharing `is_high`: `outer_true` fires 🔴 High message; `outer_false` fires whatever **Selected message** already resolved to. Both converge on the report's `processing` field.\n\nThis is how you nest conditionals with only `If` nodes: the outer pair's \"else\" value is wired from the *output of the inner pair*, not a literal — three-way branching from two binary `If` pairs."
        },
        "ui_properties": {
          "selected": false,
          "position": {
            "x": 710,
            "y": -260
          },
          "zIndex": 0,
          "width": 520,
          "height": 260,
          "selectable": true
        },
        "dynamic_properties": {},
        "dynamic_outputs": {}
      },
